Q3 Plot the relationship between âdisplâ (displacement is a representation of engine size) and âhwyâ (vehicle fuel efficiency in miles per gallon for highway driving). Describe this relationship. Note that you should place âdisplâ on the x axis as it would be used a predictor to predict hwy. In other words, âdisplâ likely has a causal relationship with âhwyâ.

#esquisser
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(mpg_con) +
 aes(x = displ, y = hwy) +
 geom_point(colour = "#112446") +
 theme_minimal()
  • Based on the scatter plot I can make the statement that as the displacement increases the hwy mpg will decrease on average. It is not a perfect negative linear relationship but it does follow that general trend.

Q4 Choose an appropriate visualization and plot the relationship between âclassâ and âhwyâ. Describe this relationship.

#esquisser()

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(mpg_con) +
 aes(x = hwy, y = class) +
 geom_boxplot(fill = "#112446") +
 theme_minimal()
  • From the separated box plots I can say that some classes of cars get drastically different hwy mpg. Pickups and SUV get the worst mileage on average while subcompacts get the most on average.

Q5 Choose an appropriate visualization and plot the distribution of âhwyâ. Comment on this distribution.

#esquisser()

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(mpg_con) +
 aes(x = hwy) +
 geom_histogram(bins = 30L, fill = "#112446") +
 theme_minimal()
  • From the distribution I can see that hwy mileage is most common at around 16 and 26 mpg with the majority from 16 to 29 mpg.

Q6 We use correlation to examine the strength of linear relationships between variables. Two variables that are strongly correlated with each other will have correlations close to either 1 (strongly positive) or -1 (strongly negative). Correlation values are only calculated (in any way that makes sense) for numeric variables.

Q7 You can develop a plot that shows a plot for each combination of variables as well as the correlations using the ggpairs function. Note that ggpairs is from the GGally package.

Use the code below to develop a ggpairs plot for this dataset. Note that I have listed the columns in the dataset that I want to see in the plot rather than including all columns. The ggpairs plot can easily become too cluttered if you include too many variables. Columns must be specified by column number. To avoid clutter, I have created two separate plots.
